    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1930-03-25T21:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1930-03-25T21:00:00-05:00" n="79"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d79">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A15a3/787c: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Chairman of the American Delegation</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Stimson</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-03-25T21:00:00-05:00"
                            >March 25, 1930—9 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>260. Our telegrams Nos. 258 and 259, March 25, 7 p.m. and 8 p.m., respectively,
                    were written after we had read your No. 161, <pb facs="0163" n="83"
                        xml:id="pg_83"/> March 25, 5 p.m. The matter is assuming considerable
                    seriousness over here, and the President is bothered. I am amazed at the cable
                    advices of which Stone is the source.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Cotton</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
